Definition 3.5. An $n$-fold Segal space $X$ is complete if • each $X_{k}$ is an $(n-1)$-fold complete Segal space, and • the simplicial space $X_{k,0,\ldots,0}$ is a complete Segal space for all $k\geq 0$.
Definition 7.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a symmetric monoidal $n$-category. An extended $\mathcal{C}$-valued topological field theory of dimension $n$ is a symmetric monoidal functor $Z\colon Cob_{n}(n)\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 2.5. ([22]) An algebraic system $\underline{B}_{\,l}=(B,0,1,\vee,\wedge,{}^{*},\rho,\mathbb{B})$ is called a local contact Boolean algebra or, briefly, local contact algebra (abbreviated as LCA or LC-algebra) if $(B,0,1,\vee,\wedge,{}^{*})$ is a Boolean algebra, $\rho$ is a binary relation on $B$ such that $(B,\rho)$ is a CA, and $\mathbb{B}$ is an ideal (possibly non proper) of $B$, satisfying the following axioms: (BC1) If $a\in\mathbb{B}$, $c\in B$ and $a\ll_{\rho}c$ then $a\ll_{\rho}b\ll_{\rho}c$ for some $b\in\mathbb{B}$; (BC2) If $a\rho b$ then there exists an element $c$ of $\mathbb{B}$ such that $a\rho(c\wedge b)$; (BC3) If $a\neq 0$ then there exists $b\in\mathbb{B}\setminus\{0\}$ such that $b\ll_{\rho}a$. We shall simply write $(B,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ for a local contact algebra. We will say that the elements of $\mathbb{B}$ are bounded and the elements of $B\setminus\mathbb{B}$ are unbounded. When $B$ is a complete Boolean algebra, the LCA $(B,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ is called a complete local contact Boolean algebra or, briefly, complete local contact algebra (abbreviated as CLCA or CLC-algebra). We will say that two local contact algebras $(B,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ and $(B_{1},\rho_{1},\mathbb{B}_{1})$ are LCA-isomorphic if there exists a Boolean isomorphism $\varphi:B\longrightarrow B_{1}$ such that, for $a,b\in B$, $a\rho b$ iff $\varphi(a)\rho_{1}\varphi(b)$, and $\varphi(a)\in\mathbb{B}_{1}$ iff $a\in\mathbb{B}$.
Definition 2.11. Let $(B,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ be a local contact algebra. We will say that $\sigma$ is a cluster in $(B,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ if $\sigma$ is a cluster in the NCA $(B,C_{\rho})$. A cluster $\sigma$ in $(B,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ is called bounded if $\sigma\cap\mathbb{B}\not=\emptyset$.
Definition 2.3. Let $(B,C)$ be a $CA$. Then a non-empty subset $\sigma$ of $B$ is called a cluster in $(B,C)$ if the following conditions are satisfied: $(K1)$ If $a,b\in\sigma$ then $aCb$; $(K2)$ If $a\vee b\in\sigma$ then $a\in\sigma$ or $b\in\sigma$; $(K3)$ If $aCb$ for every $b\in\sigma$, then $a\in\sigma$. The set of all clusters in $(B,C)$ will be denoted by $\mbox{{\rm Clust}}(B,C)$.
Definition 2.9. ([24]) Let $(B,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ be a local contact algebra. Define a binary relation $"C_{\rho}"$ on $B$ by $aC_{\rho}b\iff(a\rho b\ \mbox{\rm or}\ a,b\not\in\mathbb{B}).$ It is called the Alexandroff extension of $\rho$ relatively to the LCA $(B,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ (or, when there is no ambiguity, simply, the Alexandroff extension of $\rho$).
Definition 2.15. ([6]) Let $(A,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ be an LCA. An ideal $I$ of $A$ is called a $\delta$-ideal if $I\subseteq\mathbb{B}$ and for any $a\in I$ there exists $b\in I$ such that $a\ll_{\rho}b$. If $I_{1}$ and $I_{2}$ are two $\delta$-ideals of $(A,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ then we put $I_{1}\leq I_{2}$ iff $I_{1}\subseteq I_{2}$. We will denote by $(I(A,\rho,\mathbb{B}),\leq)$ the poset of all $\delta$-ideals of $(A,\rho,\mathbb{B})$.
Definition 2.1. An algebraic system $(B,0,1,\vee,\wedge,{}^{*},C)$ is called a contact Boolean algebra or, briefly, contact algebra (abbreviated as CA or C-algebra) ([8]) if the system $(B,0,1,\vee,\wedge,{}^{*})$ is a Boolean algebra and $C$ is a binary relation on $B$, satisfying the following axioms: (C1) If $a\not=0$ then $aCa$; (C2) If $aCb$ then $a\not=0$ and $b\not=0$; (C3) $aCb$ implies $bCa$; (C4) $aC(b\vee c)$ iff $aCb$ or $aCc$. We shall simply write $(B,C)$ for a contact algebra. The relation $C$ is called a contact relation. When $B$ is a complete Boolean algebra, we will say that $(B,C)$ is a complete contact Boolean algebra or, briefly, complete contact algebra (abbreviated as CCA or CC-algebra). We will say that two C-algebras $(B_{1},C_{1})$ and $(B_{2},C_{2})$ are CA-isomorphic iff there exists a Boolean isomorphism $\varphi:B_{1}\longrightarrow B_{2}$ such that, for each $a,b\in B_{1}$, $aC_{1}b$ iff $\varphi(a)C_{2}\varphi(b)$. Note that in this paper, by a $``$Boolean isomorphism” we understand an isomorphism in the category Bool of Boolean algebras and Boolean homomorphisms. A contact algebra $(B,C)$ is called a normal contact Boolean algebra or, briefly, normal contact algebra (abbreviated as NCA or NC-algebra) ([5],[11]) if it satisfies the following axioms (we will write $``-C$” for $``not\ C$”): (C5) If $a(-C)b$ then $a(-C)c$ and $b(-C)c^{*}$ for some $c\in B$; (C6) If $a\not=1$ then there exists $b\not=0$ such that $b(-C)a$. Note that the axioms of NC-algebras are very similar to the Efremovič axioms of proximity spaces [10]. A normal CA is called a complete normal contact Boolean algebra or, briefly, complete normal contact algebra (abbreviated as CNCA or CNC-algebra) if it is a CCA. The notion of normal contact algebra was introduced by Fedorchuk [11] under the name Boolean $\delta$-algebra as an equivalent expression of the notion of compingent Boolean algebra of de Vries (see its definition below). We call such algebras $``$normal contact algebras” because they form a subclass of the class of contact algebras and naturally arise in normal Hausdorff spaces. Note that if $0\neq 1$ then the axiom (C2) follows from the axioms (C6) and (C4). For any CA $(B,C)$, we define a binary relation $``\ll_{C}$” on $B$ (called non-tangential inclusion) by $``\ a\ll_{C}b\leftrightarrow a(-C)b^{*}\ $”. Sometimes we will write simply $``\ll$” instead of $``\ll_{C}$”.
Definition 3.2. Let MDHLC be the category whose objects are all CLCAs and whose morphisms $\varphi:(A,\rho,\mathbb{B})\longrightarrow(B,\eta,\mathbb{B}^{\prime})$ are all multi-valued maps which satisfy the following conditions: (M1) For every $a\in A$, $\varphi(a)\in I(B,\eta,\mathbb{B}^{\prime})$; (M2) $\varphi(a\wedge b)=\varphi(a)\wedge\varphi(b)$, for every $a,b\in A$; (M3) $\varphi(a)=\bigvee\{\varphi(b)\ |\ b\in\mathbb{B},b\ll a\}$, for every $a\in A$; (M4) $\varphi(0)=\{0\}$; (M5) If $a_{i},b_{i}\in\mathbb{B}$, $a_{i}\ll b_{i}$, where $i=1,2$, then $\varphi(a_{1}\vee a_{2})\subseteq\varphi(b_{1})\vee\varphi(b_{2})$; (M6) For every $b\in\mathbb{B}^{\prime}$, there exists an $a\in\mathbb{B}$ such that $b\in\varphi(a)$. The composition $\diamond$ between two morphisms $\varphi:(A_{1},\rho_{1},\mathbb{B}_{1})\longrightarrow(A_{2},\rho_{2},\mathbb{% B}_{2})$ and $\psi:(A_{2},\rho_{2},\mathbb{B}_{2})\longrightarrow(A_{3},\rho_{3},\mathbb{B}_% {3})$ is defined by $(\psi\diamond\varphi)(a)=\bigvee\{\psi(b)\ |\ b\in\varphi(a)\}$. The identity morphism $i_{A}:(A,\rho,\mathbb{B})\longrightarrow(A,\rho,\mathbb{B})$ is defined by $i_{A}(a)=I_{a}$ (see 2.16 for $I_{a}$).
Definition 4.5. The unnormalized chain complex $C(X)$ associated to $X$ is defined by $C(X)_{n}=X_{n},\;\;\;n\geq 0,$ $\partial=\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{i}(\partial_{i}^{1}-\partial_{i}^{0})\colon C(X)_% {n}\longrightarrow C(X)_{n-1},\;\;\;n>0.$
Definition 2.7 ([EM65, I.2]). Let ${\mathscr{A}}$ be a preadditive category and ${\mathscr{P}}$ a class of objects of ${\mathscr{A}}$. A sequence $\xymatrix{X\ar[r]^{f}&Y\ar[r]^{g}&Z}$ in ${\mathscr{A}}$ is said to be ${\mathscr{P}}$-exact if $gf=0$ and the sequence of abelian groups $\xymatrix{\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathscr{A}}}(P,X)\ar[r]^{-}{f_{*}}&% \operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathscr{A}}}(P,Y)\ar[r]^{-}{g_{*}}&\operatorname{Hom}_{{% \mathscr{A}}}(P,Z)}$ is exact for any $P\in{\mathscr{P}}$.
Definition 3.2. Let $S$ be a presimplicial object in a preadditive category ${\mathscr{A}}$. The unnormalized chain complex $K(S)$ associated to $S$ is defined by $K(S)_{n}=S_{n},\;\;\;n\geq 0,$ $\partial=\sum_{i=0}^{n}(-1)^{i}\partial_{i}\colon K(S)_{n}\longrightarrow K(S)% _{n-1},\;\;\;n>0.$
Definition 2.3. Let ${\mathscr{A}}$ be a preadditive category and ${\mathscr{P}}$ a class of objects in ${\mathscr{A}}$ (which need not be a “projective class” in any sense). A complex $\xymatrix{\cdots\ar[r]&C_{2}\ar[r]^{\partial_{2}}&C_{1}\ar[r]^{\partial_{1}}&C% _{0}\ar[r]^{\partial_{0}}&A}$ over $A\in{\mathscr{A}}$ is said to be ${\mathscr{P}}$-acyclic if for any $Q\in{\mathscr{P}}$ the sequence of abelian groups $\xymatrix{\cdots\ar[r]&\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathscr{A}}}(Q,C_{1})\ar[r]^{-}{{% \partial_{1}}_{*}}&\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathscr{A}}}(Q,C_{0})\ar[r]^{-}{{% \partial_{0}}_{*}}&\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathscr{A}}}(Q,A)\ar[r]&0}$ is exact.
Definition 4.2. A preadditive category ${\mathscr{A}}$ is said to be idempotent complete if any idempotent $p:E\longrightarrow E$ in ${\mathscr{A}}$ (i.e., $p^{2}=p$) has a kernel. That is, there is a morphism $i\colon\operatorname{Ker}(p)\longrightarrow E$ with $pi=0$, and for any morphism $f\colon F\longrightarrow E$, satisfying $pf=0$, there is a unique morphism $g\colon F\longrightarrow\operatorname{Ker}(p)$ such that $ig=f$.
Definition 2.1. A preadditive category is a category ${\mathscr{A}}$ together with the following data: (i) For any objects $X,Y$ in ${\mathscr{A}}$, the set of morphisms $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathscr{A}}}(X,Y)$ is an abelian group; (ii) For any morphisms $f,g\colon X\longrightarrow Y$, $h\colon W\longrightarrow X$ and $u\colon Y\longrightarrow Z$ in ${\mathscr{A}}$, the following hold $(f+g)h=fh+gh,\;\;\;u(f+g)=uf+ug.$
Definition 2.2. Let ${\mathscr{A}}$ be a preadditive category. An augmented chain complex over an object $A\in{\mathscr{A}}$ (or just a complex over $A$) is a sequence $\xymatrix{\cdots\ar[r]&C_{n}\ar[r]^{\partial_{n}}&C_{n-1}\ar[r]&\cdots\ar[r]&C% _{2}\ar[r]^{\partial_{2}}&C_{1}\ar[r]^{\partial_{1}}&C_{0}\ar[r]^{\partial_{0}% }&A}$ such that $\partial_{n}\partial_{n+1}=0$, $n\geq 0$.
Definition 2.4. Let ${\mathscr{A}}$ be a preadditive category and ${\mathscr{P}}$ a class of objects in ${\mathscr{A}}$. A ${\mathscr{P}}$-resolution of an object $A\in{\mathscr{A}}$ is a ${\mathscr{P}}$-acyclic complex $\xymatrix{\cdots\ar[r]&P_{2}\ar[r]^{\partial_{2}}&P_{1}\ar[r]^{\partial_{1}}&P% _{0}\ar[r]^{\partial_{0}}&A}$ over $A$ with $P_{n}\in{\mathscr{P}}$, $n\geq 0$.
Definition 3.1. A presimplicial object $S$ in a category ${\mathscr{C}}$ is a family of objects $(S_{n}\in{\mathscr{C}})_{n\geq 0}$ together with morphisms $\partial_{i}\colon S_{n}\longrightarrow S_{n-1},\;\;\;n\geq 1,\;\;0\leq i\leq n,$ in ${\mathscr{C}}$ satisfying the presimplicial identities $\partial_{i}\partial_{j}=\partial_{j-1}\partial_{i},\;\;\;i<j.$
Definition 2.8 ([EM65, I.2]). A closure of a class ${\mathscr{P}}$, denoted by $\overline{{\mathscr{P}}}$, is the class of all those objects $Q\in{\mathscr{A}}$ for which $\xymatrix{\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathscr{A}}}(Q,X)\ar[r]^{-}{f_{*}}&% \operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathscr{A}}}(Q,Y)\ar[r]^{-}{g_{*}}&\operatorname{Hom}_{{% \mathscr{A}}}(Q,Z)}$ is exact whenever $\xymatrix{X\ar[r]^{f}&Y\ar[r]^{g}&Z}$ is ${\mathscr{P}}$-exact.
Definition 4.6. Let $X$ be a pseudocubical object in an idempotent complete preadditive category ${\mathscr{D}}$. The chain complex $\operatorname{Ker}(1-\sigma^{X})$, denoted by $N(X)$, is called the normalized chain complex of $X$.
Definition 4.1 ([P09, 2.2]). A pseudocubical object X in a category ${\mathscr{C}}$ is a family of objects $(X_{n}\in{\mathscr{C}})_{n\geq 0}$ together with face operators $\partial_{i}^{0},\partial_{i}^{1}\colon X_{n}\longrightarrow X_{n-1},\;\;\;n% \geq 1,\;\;1\leq i\leq n,$ and pseudodegeneracy operators $s_{i}\colon X_{n-1}\longrightarrow X_{n},\;\;\;n\geq 1,\;\;1\leq i\leq n,$ satisfying the pseudocubical identities $\displaystyle\partial_{i}^{\alpha}\partial_{j}^{\varepsilon}$ $\displaystyle=\partial_{j-1}^{\varepsilon}\partial_{i}^{\alpha}\qquad i<j,% \quad\alpha,\varepsilon\in\{0,1\},$ and $\displaystyle\partial_{i}^{\alpha}s_{j}$ $\displaystyle=\begin{cases}s_{j-1}\partial_{i}^{\alpha}&i<j,\\ \textrm{id}&i=j,\\ s_{j}\partial_{i-1}^{\alpha}&i>j,\end{cases}$ for $\alpha\in\{0,1\}$.
Definition 2.6. Let $\mathfrak{a},\mathfrak{b}:{\mathcal{I}}\to\mathfrak{Cat}$ be two 2-functors and $\mathfrak{f},\mathfrak{g}:\mathfrak{a}\to\mathfrak{b}$ be 2-natural transformations. A modification $\Lambda:\mathfrak{f}\to\mathfrak{g}$ consists in giving a 2-cell $\Lambda_{i}:\mathfrak{f}_{i}\to\mathfrak{g}_{i}$ for all objects $i\in{\mathcal{I}}$ such that for all $s:i\to j$ in ${\mathcal{I}}$ the following diagram commutes $\xymatrix{\mathfrak{b}(s)\circ\mathfrak{f}_{i}\ar[r]^{\theta^{\mathfrak{f}}_{s% }}\ar[d]_{1_{\mathfrak{b}(s)}\bullet\Lambda_{i}}&\mathfrak{f}_{j}\circ% \mathfrak{a}(s)\ar[d]^{\Lambda_{j}\bullet 1_{\mathfrak{a}(s)}}\\ \mathfrak{b}(s)\circ\mathfrak{g}_{i}\ar[r]^{\theta^{\mathfrak{g}}_{s}}&% \mathfrak{g}_{j}\circ\mathfrak{a}(s)}$
Definition 2.5. Let $\mathfrak{a},\mathfrak{b}:{\mathcal{P}}\to\mathfrak{Cat}$ be two 2-functors. A 2-natural transformation $\mathfrak{f}:\mathfrak{a}\to\mathfrak{b}$ between 2 diagrams consists of the following data: (1) a 1-cell $\mathfrak{f}_{i}:\mathfrak{a}(i)\to\mathfrak{b}(i)$ of $\mathfrak{Cat}$ for every $i\in\operatorname{Ob}{\mathcal{P}}$, and (2) a natural equivalence $\theta^{\mathfrak{f}}_{s}:\mathfrak{b}(s)\circ\mathfrak{f}_{i}\to\mathfrak{f}_% {j}\circ\mathfrak{a}(s)$ for every morphism $s:i\to j$ in ${\mathcal{P}}$. such that for any two composable morphisms $s:i\to j$, $t:j\to k$ in ${\mathcal{P}}$, we have the following commutative diagram $\xymatrix@C=80pt{\mathfrak{b}(t\circ s)\circ\mathfrak{f}_{i}\ar[r]^{\Phi^{% \mathfrak{b}}(s,t)\bullet 1_{\mathfrak{f}_{i}}}\ar[dd]_{\theta^{\mathfrak{f}}_% {t\circ s}}&\mathfrak{b}(t)\circ\mathfrak{b}(s)\circ\mathfrak{f}_{i}\ar[d]^{1_% {\mathfrak{b}(t)}\bullet\theta^{\mathfrak{f}}_{s}}\\ &\mathfrak{b}(t)\circ\mathfrak{f}_{i}\circ\mathfrak{a}(s)\ar[d]^{\theta^{% \mathfrak{f}}_{t}\bullet 1_{\mathfrak{a}(s)}}\\ \mathfrak{f}_{k}\circ\mathfrak{a}(t\circ s)\ar[r]^{\mathfrak{f}_{k}\bullet\Phi% ^{\mathfrak{a}}(s,t)}&\mathfrak{f}_{k}\circ\mathfrak{a}(t)\circ\mathfrak{a}(s)}$
Definition 2.8. Let $\mathfrak{a}:{\mathcal{I}}\to\mathfrak{Cat}$ be a 2-functor. We say $\mathfrak{a}$ admits a 2-colimit if and only if there exist (1) a category $2\operatorname{colim}\mathfrak{a}$, and (2) a 2-natural transformation $\sigma:\mathfrak{a}\to 2\operatorname{colim}\mathfrak{a}$, such that for every category ${\mathcal{C}}$ the functor $(-\circ\sigma):\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathfrak{Cat}}(2\operatorname{colim}% \mathfrak{a},{\mathcal{C}})\to\operatorname{Hom}_{2{\mathcal{F}}}(\mathfrak{a}% ,{\mathcal{C}})$ is an equivalence of categories.
Definition 2.2. Let ${\mathcal{P}}$ be a small 1-category. A 2-functor (with strict identities) $\mathfrak{a}:{\mathcal{P}}\to\mathfrak{Cat}$ is given by the following data: (1) a 0-cell $\mathfrak{a}(i)$ of $\mathfrak{Cat}$ for every $i\in\operatorname{Ob}{\mathcal{P}}$, (2) a 1-cell $\mathfrak{a}(s):\mathfrak{a}(i)\to\mathfrak{a}(j)$ of $\mathfrak{Cat}$ for every morphism $s:i\to j$ in ${\mathcal{P}}$ and $\mathfrak{a}(1_{i})=1_{\mathfrak{a}(i)}$ for all $i\in\operatorname{Ob}{\mathcal{P}}$, (3) a natural equivalence $\Phi(s,t):\mathfrak{a}(t\circ s)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\rightarrow}}% \mathfrak{a}(t)\circ\mathfrak{a}(s)$ for all composable morphisms $s,t\in\operatorname{Mor}{\mathcal{P}}$, satisfying the following condition: for three composable morphisms $u,t,s\in\operatorname{Mor}{\mathcal{P}}$, we have the following commutative diagram $\xymatrix@C=80pt{\mathfrak{a}(u\circ t\circ s)\ar[r]^{\Phi(t\circ s,u)}\ar[d]_% {\Phi(s,u\circ t)}&\mathfrak{a}(u)\mathfrak{a}(t\circ s)\ar[d]^{1_{\mathfrak{a% }(u)\bullet\Phi(s,t)}}\\ \mathfrak{a}(u\circ t)\mathfrak{a}(s)\ar[r]^{\Phi(t,u)\bullet 1_{\mathfrak{a}(% s)}}&\mathfrak{a}(u)\mathfrak{a}(t)\mathfrak{a}(s)}$ A 2-functor is called strict if $\Phi(s,t)=1$, thus $\mathfrak{a}(t\circ s)=\mathfrak{a}(t)\circ\mathfrak{a}(s)$ for all composable $s,t\in\operatorname{Mor}{\mathcal{P}}$
Definition 2.7. The diagrams, 2-natural transformations, and modifications form a (strict) 2-category called $2{\mathcal{F}}({\mathcal{I}},\mathfrak{Cat})$.
Definition 7.2. Let ${\mathcal{A}}$ be an Ext-finite hereditary uniserial category with Serre duality. Let $\SS\subseteq\operatorname{ind}{\mathcal{A}}$ be the set of simple objects and let $S\in\SS$. Denote by $\SS_{S}$ the subset of $\SS$ consisting of all simple objects $T$ such that there is a path from $S$ to $T$. On $\SS_{S}$, we may define a partial ordering $\leq_{S}$ as follows. For any $T_{1},T_{2}\in\SS_{S}$, let $X_{1},X_{2}$ denote the corresponding objects as in Proposition 7.1. We then have $T_{1}\leq_{S}T_{2}\Leftrightarrow X_{1}\subseteq X_{2}.$
Definition 3.8. Given objects $(X,*)$ of $\mbox{\sc top}_{+}$ and $M$ of tmg, the exponential diagrams $X^{K}$ and $M^{K}$ are the cotensor homsets $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mbox{\sc id}}(D_{K},X)$ and $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mbox{\sc id}}(D_{K},M)$ respectively; they are $\mbox{\sc cat}(K)$-diagrams in $\mbox{\sc top}_{+}$ and tmg. Alternatively, they are the respective compositions of the exponentiation functors $X^{(\;\,)}\colon\mbox{\sc top}_{+}^{op}\rightarrow\mbox{\sc top}_{+}$ and $M^{(\;\,)}\colon\mbox{\sc top}_{+}^{op}\rightarrow\mbox{\sc tmg}$ with $D_{K}^{op}$. ∎
