6.1 Definition. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a $G$-equivariant category, and $T$ — a tangle diagram. A ${\mathcal{C}}$ coloring of $T$ is an assignment to every segment of an arc or circle a pair $(g,V),g\in G,V\in{\mathcal{C}}_{g}$ (a color) satisfying the two conditions below. In the figures, we will show a color by writing the object $V$ next to the segment, and writing $g$ next to an arrow going under the corresponding strand, as in Figure 1. Since $V$ determines $g$, we will frequently write just $V$ and omit notation of $g$. (1) For every circle, the ordered product $\prod_{i}g_{i}=1$, where the product is over all undercrossings of this circle, and $g_{i}$ are the colors of crossing strand. (2) For two segments separated by an undercrossing, the colors are related as shown in Figure 1.
8.1 Definition. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a $G$-equivariant fusion category, and $V_{i}$ —representatives of isomorphism classes of simple objects in ${\mathcal{C}}$. Then the extended Verlinde algebra of ${\mathcal{C}}$ is defined by $\widetilde{\mathcal{V}}({\mathcal{C}})=\bigoplus_{i\in I,g\in G}\operatorname{% Hom}_{{\mathcal{C}}}(V_{i},{}^{g}V_{i}).$
10.1 Definition. A $G$-equivariant fusion category with finitely many isomorphism classes of simple objects is called modular if the operator $\tilde{s}\colon\widetilde{\mathcal{V}}\to\widetilde{\mathcal{V}}$, defined by (9.3), is invertible.
3.1 Definition. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a $G$-equivariant fusion category. Then the “orbifold fusion category” ${\mathcal{C}}/G$ is a category with the following objects and morphisms: • Objects: pairs $(X,\{\varphi\}_{g})$, where $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$ and $\varphi_{g}$ is a collection of ${\mathcal{C}}$-morphisms $\varphi_{g}\colon{}^{g}X\simeq X$ such that (3.1) $\displaystyle\varphi_{1}=\operatorname{id}$ $\displaystyle\varphi_{g}R_{g}(\varphi_{h})=\varphi_{gh}$ • Morphisms: $(X,\{\varphi_{g}\})\to(Y,\{\psi_{h}\})$ are ${\mathcal{C}}$-morphisms $f\colon X\to Y$ such that $\psi_{g}\circ R_{g}(f)=f\circ\varphi_{g}$.
2.1 Definition. A $G$-equivariant category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is an abelian category with the following additional structure: $G$-grading: Decomposition ${\mathcal{C}}=\bigoplus_{g\in G}{\mathcal{C}}_{g}$ where each ${\mathcal{C}}_{g}$ is a full subcategory in ${\mathcal{C}}$. We will call objects $V\in{\mathcal{C}}_{g}$ “$g$-twisted”. In particular, objects $V\in{\mathcal{C}}_{1}$ will be called “neutral”; in physical literature, the subcategory ${\mathcal{C}}_{1}$ is usually called the “untwisted sector” Action of $G$: For each $g\in G$, we are given a functor $R_{g}\colon{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{C}}$ and functorial isomorphisms $\alpha_{gh}\colon R_{g}\circ R_{h}\xrightarrow{\sim}R_{gh}$ such that $R_{1}=\operatorname{id}$, $R_{g}{\mathcal{C}}_{h}\subset{\mathcal{C}}_{ghg^{-1}}$, and $\alpha_{g_{1}g_{2},g_{3}}\circ\alpha_{g_{1},g_{2}}=\alpha_{g_{1},g_{2}g_{3}}% \circ\alpha_{g_{2},g_{3}}$ (both sides are functorial isomorphisms $R_{g_{1}}R_{g_{2}}R_{g_{3}}\xrightarrow{\sim}R_{g_{1}g_{2}g_{3}}$). Following [T2], we will also frequently use notation ${}^{g}V$ for $R_{g}(V)$. A $G$-equivariant fusion category is a semisimple $G$-equivariant abelian category which in addition has the following structures: • Structure of a rigid monoidal category such that $\mathbf{1}$ is a simple object $R_{g}$ is a tensor functor for $X\in{\mathcal{C}}_{g},Y\in{\mathcal{C}}_{h},X\otimes Y\in{\mathcal{C}}_{gh}$ • Functorial isomorphisms $\delta_{V}\colon V\to V^{**}$, satisfying the same compatibility conditions as in the absence of $G$ (see [BK]) and additional condition $R_{g}(\delta_{V})=\delta_{R_{g}(V)}$. • A collection of functorial isomorphisms $R_{V,W}\colon V\otimes W\to{}^{g}W\otimes V$ for every $V\in{\mathcal{C}}_{g},W\in{\mathcal{C}}_{h}$, satisfying an analog of the pentagon axiom (see [T2, Section 2.2]).
8.5 Definition. Let $\varphi\colon V_{i}\to{}^{g_{1}}V_{i}$, $\psi\colon V_{j}\to{}^{g_{2}}V_{j}$. Then $[\varphi]*[\psi]\in\widetilde{\mathcal{V}}$ is defined by • If ${}^{g_{2}}V_{j},V_{i}$ are not isomorphic, then $[\varphi]*[\psi]=0$ • If there exists an isomorphism $\lambda\colon{}^{g_{2}}V_{j}\xrightarrow{\sim}V_{i}$, then $[\varphi]*[\psi]=d_{i}^{-1}[V_{j}\xrightarrow{\psi}{}^{g_{2}}V_{j}\xrightarrow% {\lambda}V_{i}\xrightarrow{\varphi}{}^{g_{1}}V_{i}\xrightarrow{R_{g_{1}}(% \lambda^{-1})}{}^{g_{1}g_{2}}V_{j}]$ where, as before, $d_{i}=\dim V_{i}=\dim{}^{g_{2}}V_{j}=d_{j}$.
Definition 5.7. A partially ordered set $I$ is directed if for any $i,i^{\prime}\in I$ there exists $i^{\prime\prime}\in I$ with $i^{\prime\prime}\geq i$ and $i^{\prime\prime}\geq i^{\prime}$; $I$ is called strongly directed if $i\geq i^{\prime}$ and $i\leq i^{\prime}$ implies $i=i^{\prime}$. A directed set $I$ is called cofinite if every $i\in I$ has only a finite number of predecessors.
Definition 3.2. In the equivariant model structure on ${\cal S}^{D}$ a morphism $f\colon\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{X}}}{X}}\mathstrut\rightarrow% \smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{Y}}}{Y}}\mathstrut$ is a • weak equivalence if and only if $\operatorname{\textup{map}}(\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{O}}}{O}}% \mathstrut,f)$ is a weak equivalence of spaces for any orbit $\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{O}}}{O}}\mathstrut$; • fibration if and only if $\operatorname{\textup{map}}(\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{O}}}{O}}% \mathstrut,f)$ is a fibration of spaces for any orbit $\smash{\underset{\widetilde{\hphantom{O}}}{O}}\mathstrut$; • cofibration if and only if it has the left lifting property with respect to any trivial fibration.
Definition 5.2. A representative of a morphism from a pro-object $X$ indexed by a cofiltering $I$ to a pro-object $Y$ indexed by a cofiltering $K$ is a function $\theta\colon K\rightarrow I$ (not necessarily order-preserving) and morphisms $f_{k}\colon X_{\theta(k)}\rightarrow Y_{k}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ for each $k\in K$ such that if $k\leq k^{\prime}$ in $K$, then for some $i\in I$ with $i\geq\theta(k)$ and $i\geq\theta(k^{\prime})$ the following diagram commutes: $\xymatrix{X_{i}\ar[r]^{b_{i,\theta(k^{\prime})}}\ar[dr]_{b_{i,\theta(k)}}&X_{% \theta(k^{\prime})}\ar[r]^{f_{k^{\prime}}}&Y_{k^{\prime}}\ar[d]^{b_{k^{\prime}% ,k}}\\ &X_{\theta(k)}\ar[r]^{f_{k}}&Y_{k}.}$ A representative $(\phi,\{g_{k}\})$ rarefies the representative $(\theta,\{f_{k}\})$ if for every $k\in K$, $\phi(k)\geq\theta(k)$ and there exists a bonding map $b_{\phi(k),{\theta(k)}}\colon X_{\phi(k)}\rightarrow X_{\theta(k)}$ with $g_{k}=f_{k}\circ b_{\phi(k),{\theta(k)}}$. A representative $(\theta,\{f_{k}\})$ is called strict [12, p. 36] if $\theta$ is a functor and the maps $\{f_{k}\colon X_{\theta(k)}\rightarrow Y_{k}\;|\;k\in K\}$ constitute a natural transformation $f\colon X\circ\theta\rightarrow Y$. In other words, the representative of a morphism is strict if all $f_{k}$ fit into commutative squares of the following form: $\xymatrix{X_{\theta(k^{\prime})}\ar[r]^{f_{k^{\prime}}}\ar[d]_{b_{\theta(k^{% \prime}),\theta(k)}}&Y_{k^{\prime}}\ar[d]^{b_{k^{\prime},k}}\\ X_{\theta(k)}\ar[r]^{f_{k}}&Y_{k}}$ A strict representative $(\theta,\{f_{k}\})$ is called levelwise if the domain and range of $f$ are indexed by the same indexing category $I$ and $\theta=\mathrm{Id}_{I}$.
Definition 5.1. A small, non-empty category $I$ is cofiltering if for every pair of objects $i$ and $j$ there exists an object $k$ together with maps $k\rightarrow i$ and $k\rightarrow j$; and for every pair of morphisms $i\underset{g}{\overset{f}{\rightrightarrows}}j$ there exists a map $h\colon k\rightarrow i$ with $fh=gh$. A diagram is said to be cofiltering if its indexing category is so. For a category $\mathcal{C}$, the category pro-${\bf\mathcal{C}}$ has objects all cofiltering diagrams in $\mathcal{C}$, and the set of morphisms from a pro-object $X$ indexed by a cofiltering $J$ into a pro-object $Y$ indexed by a cofiltering $I$ is given by the following formula: $\operatorname{\textup{Hom}}_{\text{pro-$\mathcal{C}$}}(X,Y)=\lim_{i}\mathop{% \textup{colim}}_{j}\operatorname{\textup{Hom}}_{\mathcal{C}}(X_{j},Y_{i}).$ A pro-object (pro-morphism) is an object (morphism) of pro-$\mathcal{C}$. The structure maps of diagrams which represent pro-objects are also called bonding maps and denoted by $b_{i_{1},i_{2}}\colon Y_{i_{1}}\rightarrow Y_{i_{2}}$.
Definition 1.3. A model category $\mathcal{C}$ is called class-cofibrantly generated if (1) there exists a class $I$ of maps in $\mathcal{C}$ (called a class of generating cofibrations) that permits (either functorial or non-functorial version of) the generalized small object argument and such that a map is a trivial fibration if and only if it has the right lifting property with respect to every element of $I$, and (2) there exists a class $J$ of maps in $\mathcal{C}$ (called a class of generating trivial cofibrations) that permits (either functorial or non-functorial version of) the generalized small object argument and such that a map is a fibration if and only if it has the right lifting property with respect to every element of $J$.
Definition 3.1. (a) For $X$ in $\Gamma$ we define $\bar{G}X=\textup{id}_{X}(\mathbb{A})$. If $\varphi:X\to Y$ is a map in $\Gamma$ then $\textup{id}_{Y}\varphi=\varphi$, hence $\varphi\textup{id}_{X}(\mathbb{A})\subseteq\textup{id}_{Y}(\mathbb{A})$, and therefore $\varphi$ induces, via left multiplication, a group homomorphism $\bar{G}X\to\bar{G}Y$. Thus $\bar{G}$ is a functor from $\Gamma$ to $\mathop{\mathcal{A}b}\nolimits$. (b) If $X$ is an arbitrary nonempty countable graph then we denote by $X_{\Gamma}$ the category whose objects are isomorphisms $c:X\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\cong}}{{\longrightarrow}}X_{0}$ with $X_{0}$ in $\Gamma$. Morphisms of $X_{\Gamma}$ are maps $X_{0}\to X_{0}$ under $X$. Define $\bar{G}c=\bar{G}X_{0}$ and $\bar{G}X=\mathop{\rm colim}_{c\in X_{\Gamma}}\bar{G}c.$ The values of $\bar{G}$ on morphisms are defined in the obvious way. We may view this as an extension of (a) since for $X$ in $\Gamma$ the category $X_{\Gamma}$ contains a distinguished element $\textup{id}_{X}$. (c) If $X$ is an arbitrary nonempty graph then we denote by $[X]$ the category of inclusions whose objects are nonempty countable subgraphs $C\subseteq X$. Define $\bar{G}X=\mathop{\rm colim}_{C\in[X]}\bar{G}C.$ Again this agrees with (b) since for $X$ nonempty and countable, $\textup{id}_{X}$ is the terminal element of $[X]$. A map $f:X\to Y$ induces, by taking images, a map $[X]\to[Y]$, which in turn induces a map $\bar{G}f$ of colimits.
Definition 5.2. The enriched Bousfield colocalization of $\mathcal{M}$ with respect to $\mathcal{K}$ is a $\mathcal{V}$-model structure $\mathcal{M}^{\mathcal{K}}$ on $\mathcal{M}$ such that: (i) The fibrations in $\mathcal{M}^{\mathcal{K}}$ are the same as the fibrations in $\mathcal{M}$. (ii) The weak equivalences in $\mathcal{M}^{\mathcal{K}}$ are the $\mathcal{K}$-colocal equivalences. (iii) The cofibrant objects in $\mathcal{M}^{\mathcal{L}}$ are the $\mathcal{K}$-colocal objects.
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be a monoidal model category. A monoidal $\mathcal{V}$-model category is a monoidal model category $\mathcal{M}$ together with a monoidal Quillen adjunction $i\colon\mathcal{V}\rightleftarrows\mathcal{M}\colon r$.
Definition 6.2. Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a $C$-coloured operad. A subset $J\subseteq C$ is called an ideal relative to $\mathcal{P}$ if $\mathcal{P}(c_{1},\ldots,c_{n};c)=0$ whenever $n\geq 1$, $c\in J$, and $c_{i}\not\in J$ for some $i\in\{1,\ldots,n\}$. A subset $I\subseteq C$ is called a coideal relative to $\mathcal{P}$ if $I=C\setminus J$ for some ideal $J$ relative to $\mathcal{P}$.
Definition 4.2. Let $F$ be an endofunctor on a category $\mathcal{M}$. The extension of $F$ over $\mathcal{M}^{C}$ is the endofunctor on $\mathcal{M}^{C}$, which we keep denoting by $F$, given by $F\mathbf{X}=(FX(c))_{c\in C}$. If $F$ is equipped with an augmentation $\eta$ or a coaugmentation $\varepsilon$, then $\eta_{\mathbf{X}}=(\eta_{X(c)})_{c\in C}$ and $\varepsilon_{\mathbf{X}}=(\varepsilon_{X(c)})_{c\in C}$, respectively.
Definition 5.1. The enriched Bousfield localization of $\mathcal{M}$ with respect to $\mathcal{L}$ is a $\mathcal{V}$-model structure $\mathcal{M}_{\mathcal{L}}$ on $\mathcal{M}$ such that: (i) The cofibrations in $\mathcal{M}_{\mathcal{L}}$ are the same as the cofibrations in $\mathcal{M}$. (ii) The weak equivalences in $\mathcal{M}_{\mathcal{L}}$ are the $\mathcal{L}$-local equivalences. (iii) The fibrant objects in $\mathcal{M}_{\mathcal{L}}$ are the $\mathcal{L}$-local objects.
Definition 3.1. A semi model category structure on a category $\mathcal{V}$ is given by three classes of distinguished morphisms called weak equivalences, fibrations and cofibrations, satisfying the following axioms: (i) $\mathcal{V}$ is complete and cocomplete (ii) Let $f$ and $g$ be two composable morphisms. If any two among $f$, $g$ and $g\circ f$ are weak equivalences, then so is the third (iii) The classes of weak equivalences, fibrations and cofibrations are closed under retracts. (iv) The class of fibrations has the right lifting property with respect to the class of trivial cofibrations with cofibrant domain. The class of trivial fibrations has the right lifting property with respect to the class of cofibrations with cofibrant domain. (v) There exist functorial factorizations of any morphism with cofibrant domain into a cofibration followed by a trivial fibration and also into a trivial cofibration followed by a fibration. (vi) The initial object is cofibrant. (vii) The classes of fibrations and trivial fibrations are stable under pullbacks and (possibly transfinite) composites.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{V}$ be a monoidal model category. A $\mathcal{V}$-model category is a category $\mathcal{M}$ enriched, tensored and cotensored over $\mathcal{V}$ together with a model structure such that the tensor, enrichment and cotensor define a Quillen adjunction of two variables, and for every cofibrant object $X$ in $\mathcal{M}$, the map $\widetilde{I}\otimes X\longrightarrow I\otimes X$ is a weak equivalence in $\mathcal{M}$, where $\widetilde{I}\rightarrow I$ denotes any cofibrant approximation of the unit.
